passage: One of humanity's greatest accomplishments has been sending a man to the moon. In the 1960s, during the Cold War between the Soviet Union and the United States, a period of heightened tension between the two nations, the countries were engaged in something called the Space Race, a period of one-upmanship where each power tried to perform a more impressive astronautical feat than the other. Both countries sent probes to different moons and planets, with Russia claiming to have the first human in space. The United States tried to trump this claim by sending a manned aircraft to the moon. Many animals were sent to space during this time; among them, a monkey blasted off. The monkey, which hitched a ride on a U.S. rocket, was not the first animal in space. United States scientists placed fruit flies in a rocket in 1947 to understand how radiation affects living organisms at that height. The monkey that went to space a year after the fruit flies did not technically enter orbit. This title belonged to a Russian dog named Laika, which was sent into orbit in a satellite in 1957. Although there would probably be ethical objections to such an experiment now, a few decades ago, the Soviet Union determined that dogs, as mammals, would respond to the effects of orbit in a manner similar to that of humans. As adventurous animals, dogs might have been very receptive to the excursion of hopping into a metal aircraft and blasting off to parts unknown. Laika was a particularly attractive candidate to the Soviets because she was a stray dog, which led researchers to believe that she would be resilient under pressure. Small enough to fit into a space capsule and attractive enough to make a pleasing photo subject for newspapers, two-year old Laika was taken from an animal shelter and selected for the mission. Laika died in orbit, but it is not entirely clear what happened to her because of conflicting reports. Russian state media reported that the dog had lived in space for a week, but this is an apocryphal story. It is unlikely that Laika would have been able to survive the incredibly high temperatures caused by the shuttle jetting through the atmosphere. Still, as the first animal to reach orbit, Laika has become immortalized as an integral part of the Space Race.

passage: Multiple other languages greatly influence the English language. Words with many syllables very often have a root found in either Greek or Latin, while much of English grammar and its shorter words are derived from a form of German. There is almost endless debate on how to name something new, and some words we say now may have been different words altogether because of a debate over which languages or meanings to incorporate. Take for instance, the bicycle. When it first hit the mainstream, English speakers referred to the invention as a "velocipede," a term that may be familiar to Russian speakers, who have kept the term as their way of referring to a bicycle. This is not the only example of a name that has changed with time. William Herschel discovered Uranus about 250 years ago, and decided to name it after the reigning ruler of the time - King George III. He specifically referred to it as "The Georgian Planet". After time, though, this planet became named 'Uranus' after the Greek deity of the sky. The old name for the month of February was a bit odd. In Old English, February was called Sprout Kale-Monath because it was the month when sea-kale, a type of cabbage, would begin to grow. This would mean that the original name for February could loosely be interpreted as meaning "Cabbage Month". There are also accounts of the month being named Solmonath. Interpretations differ, but even though the literal translation is "mud-month", historians believe a more accurate meaning is "month of cake," because the Anglo-Saxons would bake food to serve to their gods. Even Vitamin C almost had a strange name. When Hungarian physiologist Albert Szent-Gyorgi discovered Vitamin C, he wasn't entirely sure about the chemical's molecular structure. However, he was convinced that it was a sugar, and as sugars end in -ose (as in the examples of glucose, fructose, and fructose), he called it Godnose, a play on words where the scientist intended to convey that "God knows what this is made of". The physiologist's publisher rejected this clever name, and today we refer to the sugar as Vitamin C. In history, even small changes can lead to an entirely different name.

passage: When vinyl players first came out, it was thought that they would lead to the death of music. The reality of the situation has been quite different. The reason behind these apocalyptic proclamations was mainly due to the live nature of music - before that time, almost all music was played in-person rather than pre-recorded. Logic at the time dictated that if people could have music in their homes, there would be no sense in seeing musicians perform live. A second perceived end-times of music came when CDs hit the mainstream. It was true that musicians survived with their livelihood despite the advent of vinyl players, and that some artists were even made more popular because their work was available on a vinyl disc, but making music portable surely should have been judgement day for musicians. After all, if someone could take music to their office, car, or barbeque, then what was the purpose of seeing a touring musician? Nonetheless, musicians had largely weathered the storm. The real trouble, however, began when music started to migrate to the online world. Whereas previously, many artists would have been able to sell records and CDs as means of making money that would supplement the income they made from their tours, making music available online actually did decrease profits for musicians. The first such service that provided music to the public, LimeWire, did so for free and illegally, and the creator eventually had to pay a fine of more than $100 million to the Recording Industry Association of America. However, legal platforms created as a form of online radio meant to replace LimeWire, such as Spotify or Pandora, often pay musicians very little for their work. Musicians often must also split industry profits with lawyers, recording agencies, music distributors, venues, and sound engineers, meaning that the amount of money some musicians end up taking at the end of the day is very little unless they manage to be successful while still being entirely independent. There are some factors that could give musicians hope. For one, estimates from different sites speculate that musicians earn an average of $19 per hour - a decent salary that can be grown even more with the proper sales skills. Vinyl players and discs, once thought of as obsolete, are now experiencing a renaissance as music listeners wish to have better sound quality and a physical display of their musical tastes. Singer and songwriter Adele recently made big news when her 2015 album went diamond, meaning that it obtained over 10 million sales in physical copies. While it does seem increasingly difficult for musicians to make a livelihood from their profession, industries and artists will continue to find more effective ways to turn a profit, and reports of the death of the music in the future - if the past is any indicator will be greatly exaggerated.
